		@H Historical Background @L
		Romans believed the gods were real and their influence, happiness, or wrath could affect the mortal world in many ways. Not only did Romans think gods were real, but they thought that all gods were real. In their mind, enemies had powerful allies on their side if their pantheon and culture was well developed. @L@L
		You may note the many similarities between Hellenic and Latin pantheons. This is no coincidence, since as was discussed before, Greeks had a significant presence in Italy dating back to the Bronze Age. Classical Greeks did not know about the Bronze Age collapse directly, but rather thought of it as a time of heroes, the conquest of Troy and Crete, as well as the time when gods walked the earth amongst the mortals, often in disguise. @L@L
		Romans were envious of the Greek culture and how old and established their culture was. Their institutions, pantheon, and overall culture was heavily inspired by the Greeks, even going as far as to send envoys to bring democracy back to Rome after the Etruscan kings were banished from the city. @L@L
		One other example would be how Romans envied the Odyssey and its cultural tradition on the Greeks as a whole. They developed a very likely fictional work by the Roman poet Virgil which was called Aeneid. In this epic poem, it's stated that Romans were escaped refugees from Troy after its conquest by the Mycenean Greeks, led by the Aeneas who was already a character mentioned in the Greek Odyssey. @L@L
		One of the biggest strengths of the Roman state and why it was able to conquer much of the known world was the ability to integrate parts of the culture from conquered peoples into their own. @L@L@L

